  "notes": "Spectrum 2's full ramps are asymmetric: chromatic hues run 100-1600 (16 steps) while gray runs 25-1000 (13 steps). This file shows the shared 100-1000 window where every scale defines a token under the same name, so indexing is uniform; the omitted steps are gray-25/50/75 (near-background tints) and the chromatic deep shades 1100-1600. appBg and subtleBg are null because Spectrum's app backgrounds live on the omitted light end of gray: background-base-color = gray-25 (rgb(255, 255, 255) light / rgb(17, 17, 17) dark) and background-layer-1-color = gray-50. roleMapping grounding, from the semantic aliases in the same token file and spectrum.adobe.com usage guidance: uiBg = gray-100 (neutral-subtle-background-color-default, menu-item default background) with hover/active following the documented +1-index interactive-state progression (e.g. stack-item selected background 100 -> 200 -> 300); borderSubtle = gray-200 (decorative borders per docs, with gray-300), border = gray-400 (field borders: text field, action button), borderStrong = gray-600 (control borders: switch, checkbox, radio); textSubtle = gray-700 (neutral-subdued-content-color-default), text = gray-800 (body-color, neutral-content-color-default; headings use gray-900); solid = index 8 (accent-background-color-default = accent-color-900, white text) and solidHover = index 9 (accent-background-color-hover = accent-color-1000). Semantic aliases: accent/informative = blue, negative = red, positive = green, and 'warning' is Spectrum's 'notice' semantic which aliases orange (notice-color-* -> orange-*), not yellow. Tokens also define a 'wireframe' scheme (omitted) and transparent-white/black alpha ramps for use over images. spectrum.adobe.com docs still describe the Spectrum 1 grid (11 grays 50-900, 13 colors with 14 steps, gray-100 default background); values here are Spectrum 2 from @adobe/spectrum-tokens v14.15.0, where the light/dark sets correspond to the light and dark themes."
